
[1]strew

   STREW, v.t. [This verb is written straw, strew, or strow; straw is
   nearly obsolete, and strow is obsolescent. Strew is generally used.]

   1. To scatter; to spread by scattering; always applied to dry
   substances separable into parts or particles; as, to strew seed in
   beds; to strew sand on or over a floor; to strew flowers over a grave.

   2. To spread by being scattered over.

   The snow which does the top of Pindus strew.

   Is thine alone the seed that strews the plain?

   3. To scatter loosely.

   And strewd his mangled limbs about the field.
